1
00:00:09,161 --> 00:00:11,841
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

2
00:00:23,161 --> 00:00:26,241
(SIRENS BLARING IN THE DISTANCE)

3
00:00:39,001 --> 00:00:41,641
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

4
00:01:01,481 --> 00:01:02,841
-DOCTOR: Hey, you!
-(COUGHS)

5
00:01:07,721 --> 00:01:08,761
DOCTOR: Hello, there.

6
00:01:10,681 --> 00:01:14,121
Oh! Hello. (GRUNTING)

7
00:01:15,881 --> 00:01:18,241
-Hello?
-Hello!

8
00:01:18,841 --> 00:01:21,761
-What are you doing?
-I was setting a trap!

9
00:01:21,841 --> 00:01:24,001
-A trap?
-DOCTOR: Are you rough?

10
00:01:24,081 --> 00:01:26,321
-YOUNG GRANT: What happened?
-I tried it out!

11
00:01:26,401 --> 00:01:28,681
-How?
-Accidentally.

12
00:01:28,761 --> 00:01:30,201
-(SNEEZES)
-Bless you.

13
00:01:30,281 --> 00:01:31,321
Thanks.

14
00:01:31,481 --> 00:01:32,681
-What's your name?
-Grant.

15
00:01:32,761 --> 00:01:35,441
-Hello, Grant. What floor is this?
-Sixty.

16
00:01:36,841 --> 00:01:38,081
(YELLS)

17
00:01:40,121 --> 00:01:41,681
Would it be all right if I came in?

18
00:01:41,761 --> 00:01:43,241
Oh, I have to ask my mum.

19
00:01:44,401 --> 00:01:46,041
-Ow!
-Mum! Wake up!

20
00:01:46,401 --> 00:01:47,601
(CONTINUES COUGHING)

21
00:01:48,761 --> 00:01:50,081
(CRACKLING)

22
00:01:51,561 --> 00:01:52,601
(GRUNTING)

23
00:02:03,361 --> 00:02:04,601
(GROANS)

24
00:02:08,881 --> 00:02:11,201
Mum says you can come in.
You're expected.

25
00:02:11,561 --> 00:02:13,361
(PANTING) Expected?

26
00:02:13,881 --> 00:02:15,161
(SCREAMS)

27
00:02:19,401 --> 00:02:21,961
(STRAINING)

28
00:02:40,241 --> 00:02:43,241
-So, did you say I was expected?
-Yeah.

29
00:02:43,321 --> 00:02:44,601
Who did you say I was?

30
00:02:44,681 --> 00:02:47,001
I told her I saw an old guy
at the window.

31
00:02:51,841 --> 00:02:52,881
(SNEEZES)

32
00:02:54,561 --> 00:02:56,201
Ho, ho, ho, ho.

33
00:02:59,001 --> 00:03:00,681
Merry Christmas, Grant.

34
00:03:12,241 --> 00:03:15,561
Mum and Dad are asleep now.
I can get you back on the roof.

35
00:03:15,641 --> 00:03:17,281
-I know the way.
-Shh.

36
00:03:17,761 --> 00:03:20,361
-What are you doing?
-Take a look at that picture.

37
00:03:22,681 --> 00:03:24,321
-Okay.
-Now, this one.

38
00:03:25,241 --> 00:03:27,961
Take a good long look.
Takes a moment to see it.

39
00:03:28,641 --> 00:03:29,881
YOUNG GRANT: See what?

40
00:03:29,961 --> 00:03:33,441
Superman and Clark Kent
are one and the same person.

41
00:03:36,001 --> 00:03:37,721
-Are you serious?
-Yeah.

42
00:03:38,161 --> 00:03:40,321
Look, I drew specs on Superman.

43
00:03:40,401 --> 00:03:42,361
Everyone knows they're the same person.

44
00:03:45,401 --> 00:03:46,441
DOCTOR: Uh...

45
00:03:48,001 --> 00:03:50,761
Well, Lois Lane doesn't.
And she's a reporter.

46
00:03:56,521 --> 00:03:58,641
DOCTOR: Why did they call him
Spider-Man? Don't they like him?

47
00:03:58,721 --> 00:04:01,921
He was bitten by a radioactive spider
and guess what happened?

48
00:04:02,881 --> 00:04:05,001
Radiation poisoning, I should think.

49
00:04:05,401 --> 00:04:07,361
No, he got special powers.

50
00:04:07,441 --> 00:04:11,201
What, vomiting, hair loss and death.
Fat lot of use.

51
00:04:12,281 --> 00:04:13,361
Hey.

52
00:04:15,441 --> 00:04:17,121
-What do you think?
-YOUNG GRANT: That looks...

53
00:04:17,201 --> 00:04:18,761
-DOCTOR: I know.
-Cheap.

54
00:04:19,321 --> 00:04:21,041
-Oh, shut up.
-(SNEEZES)

55
00:04:22,041 --> 00:04:24,201
-Got a cold there, Grant?
-I always get a cold on Christmas.

56
00:04:24,561 --> 00:04:27,001
Me too. What an invasion.

57
00:04:28,241 --> 00:04:30,561
-Where did you get that from?
-My pocket.

58
00:04:30,641 --> 00:04:32,361
How did you put a glass of water
in your pocket?

59
00:04:32,441 --> 00:04:35,641
Skills. Now, hush.
I got a lot of work to do.

60
00:04:35,721 --> 00:04:37,001
Take this.

61
00:04:39,201 --> 00:04:40,481
Ah.

62
00:04:41,001 --> 00:04:42,641
-Who are you?
-The Doctor.

63
00:04:42,721 --> 00:04:45,321
-Yeah, but who are you?
-The Doctor.

64
00:04:45,401 --> 00:04:47,321
Which one, though?
There's lots of doctors.

65
00:04:47,401 --> 00:04:49,361
The one, the main one. The original.

66
00:04:49,441 --> 00:04:51,601
I started it. They're all based on me.

67
00:04:51,681 --> 00:04:54,481
Now, everyone who wants to sound clever
calls themselves doctor.

68
00:04:54,561 --> 00:04:55,841
Bandwagon.

69
00:04:55,921 --> 00:04:58,521
In a comic book,
you know what you'd be called?

70
00:04:58,681 --> 00:05:00,201
Doctor Mysterio.

71
00:05:01,521 --> 00:05:03,401
Well, I like that.

72
00:05:03,481 --> 00:05:06,361
Doctor Mysterio! I'll have that.

73
00:05:07,321 --> 00:05:09,561
-Nearly ready.
-What is it?

74
00:05:09,641 --> 00:05:13,361
Well, in terms
that you would understand...

75
00:05:13,961 --> 00:05:14,961
Sorry, there aren't any.

76
00:05:15,041 --> 00:05:20,441
(STAMMERS) It's a time distortion
equalizer thingy.

77
00:05:20,521 --> 00:05:21,521
A what?

78
00:05:21,601 --> 00:05:24,241
Well, there's a little bit of
a localised disruption here in New York,

79
00:05:24,321 --> 00:05:26,161
so, uh, my fault, actually.

80
00:05:26,241 --> 00:05:28,281
Hopefully, this will
make it all calm down.

81
00:05:28,361 --> 00:05:29,721
I don't understand.

82
00:05:29,801 --> 00:05:32,601
DOCTOR: Uh, do you know what
a lightning conductor is?

83
00:05:32,681 --> 00:05:33,961
-YOUNG GRANT: Yeah.
-Well, it's not like that.

84
00:05:34,041 --> 00:05:37,321
-I thought you were setting a trap.
-I was. To protect this.

85
00:05:37,441 --> 00:05:40,561
I don't want anyone turning it off,
or stealing it for a Christmas tree.

86
00:05:40,641 --> 00:05:43,401
-But it looks like a Christmas tree.
-Of course it does. It's science.

87
00:05:44,641 --> 00:05:46,881
-Do you want to turn the lights on?
-Can I?

88
00:05:46,961 --> 00:05:48,521
Go on. It's Christmas day.

89
00:05:48,601 --> 00:05:49,841
-What do I do?
-Ah.

90
00:05:52,561 --> 00:05:55,121
Right. Put this into this.

91
00:05:56,081 --> 00:05:58,121
And you flick
all those little switches on.

92
00:05:58,201 --> 00:05:59,401
(BEEPING)

93
00:06:03,081 --> 00:06:04,161
YOUNG GRANT: Nothing's happening.

94
00:06:04,241 --> 00:06:06,961
Yeah, because now,
we get to the cool bit. Come here.

95
00:06:09,001 --> 00:06:11,321
Do you see that little door there?
Pop it open.

96
00:06:12,641 --> 00:06:14,721
Now we turn on the lights.

97
00:06:15,041 --> 00:06:16,921
Pop the gemstone right in there.

98
00:06:17,321 --> 00:06:18,321
What gemstone?

99
00:06:18,401 --> 00:06:20,881
The gemstone that I gave you.
Pop it right in there.

100
00:06:20,961 --> 00:06:23,801
-(WHISPERS) That was a gemstone?
-Well, it's more than just a gemstone.

101
00:06:24,081 --> 00:06:27,321
It's also like a kind of
on-board computer. Come here.

102
00:06:28,481 --> 00:06:32,281
Can you see...
Can you see that little yellow star?

103
00:06:32,601 --> 00:06:33,841
Near the end of that curve.

104
00:06:34,281 --> 00:06:35,681
It comes from near there.

105
00:06:36,801 --> 00:06:39,241
Formed in the heart of a red hole.

106
00:06:40,201 --> 00:06:44,121
Stabilised a pure dwarf star crystal.
The gemstone is intuitive.

107
00:06:44,361 --> 00:06:45,881
It knows what you want.

108
00:06:46,121 --> 00:06:49,081
And it draws energy from
the nearest star to make it happen.

109
00:06:49,161 --> 00:06:51,881
There's only four of them
left in the universe.

110
00:06:52,881 --> 00:06:57,961
The apocalypse monks of the Andorax
called this one the "Hassandra,"

111
00:06:58,961 --> 00:07:01,921
the ghost of love and wishes.

112
00:07:03,281 --> 00:07:05,521
Okay then, pop it in.

113
00:07:05,641 --> 00:07:07,681
I thought it was medicine.

114
00:07:09,561 --> 00:07:11,601
-What?
-It looked like medicine.

115
00:07:13,281 --> 00:07:14,321
What have you done with it?

116
00:07:14,401 --> 00:07:16,201
Well, you gave me medicine
and a glass of water

117
00:07:16,281 --> 00:07:17,881
and you said you were a doctor.

118
00:07:18,921 --> 00:07:22,281
-I thought it was for my cough.
-Oh... You swallowed it.

119
00:07:22,361 --> 00:07:25,241
You can't go around swallowing things.
What age are you, 367

120
00:07:25,321 --> 00:07:27,721
-Eight.
-(MACHINE WHIRRING)

121
00:07:28,961 --> 00:07:30,521
Am I gonna get sick?

122
00:07:31,041 --> 00:07:32,841
No, no, no, no. Quite the opposite.

123
00:07:33,201 --> 00:07:35,201
The opposite? What's the opposite?

124
00:07:37,681 --> 00:07:39,681
-What happened?
-DOCTOR: Nothing.

125
00:07:39,761 --> 00:07:41,001
What's wrong with me?

126
00:07:41,721 --> 00:07:45,241
Well, uh, you've got a cough
and a slight case of levitation.

127
00:07:47,641 --> 00:07:49,641
-Stay calm.
-What happens if I don't stay calm?

128
00:07:49,721 --> 00:07:52,441
-(GRUNTS) Don't panic!
-What happens if I panic?

129
00:07:52,521 --> 00:07:55,041
(BOTH SCREAMING)

130
00:07:59,921 --> 00:08:02,641
(BABY CRYING)

131
00:08:12,801 --> 00:08:14,761
(WHISPERS) Oh, hey, you're all right.

132
00:08:15,201 --> 00:08:17,521
Hi. You're okay.

133
00:08:17,641 --> 00:08:19,721
(BABY COOING)

134
00:08:20,721 --> 00:08:21,921
Yeah.

135
00:08:23,761 --> 00:08:26,401
(SHUSHING)

136
00:08:26,561 --> 00:08:30,401
Hey, Mrs Lombard.
No, don't worry. Jennifer's fine.

137
00:08:30,841 --> 00:08:33,561
She just woke up
and I'm gonna put her back to sleep.

138
00:08:34,201 --> 00:08:37,321
No, it's okay, Mrs Lombard,
It's what you pay me for.

139
00:08:38,121 --> 00:08:40,321
Okay. Goodnight.

140
00:08:45,961 --> 00:08:48,441
DOCTOR: (YELLS) You need to calm...

141
00:08:51,361 --> 00:08:53,401
YOUNG GRANT: What's happened to me?

142
00:08:54,441 --> 00:08:57,361
Intuitive crystal,
plus too many comic books.

143
00:08:57,441 --> 00:08:59,881
The gemstone is giving you
what it thinks you want!

144
00:08:59,961 --> 00:09:02,641
(SCREAMS) You're a superhero!

145
00:09:07,281 --> 00:09:09,281
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

146
00:09:47,681 --> 00:09:49,321
MR BROCK: Any questions after today

147
00:09:49,401 --> 00:09:51,721
can be handled by
Miss Schuster or Miss Segal

148
00:09:51,801 --> 00:09:53,721
who can be contacted
on the e-mail addresses

149
00:09:53,801 --> 00:09:55,481
provided in your welcome pack.

150
00:09:55,561 --> 00:09:58,321
That's all we have time for,
ladies and gentlemen.

151
00:09:58,481 --> 00:10:00,521
I hope you had a stimulating day.

152
00:10:00,681 --> 00:10:03,001
And maybe saw a little of
what makes Harmony Shoal

153
00:10:03,201 --> 00:10:06,441
the foremost innovator
in science and technology

154
00:10:06,521 --> 00:10:08,081
the world over.

155
00:10:08,201 --> 00:10:12,001
Like we always say,
we're here to open your minds.

156
00:10:12,641 --> 00:10:15,041
LUCY: Mr Brock, just one more question.

157
00:10:15,401 --> 00:10:16,761
I've been looking into your funding,

158
00:10:17,121 --> 00:10:20,841
and you seem to have a lot of
benefactors for a research institute.

159
00:10:20,921 --> 00:10:23,041
Well, the world is changing,
Miss Fletcher.

160
00:10:23,641 --> 00:10:24,881
Science got sexy.

161
00:10:25,561 --> 00:10:29,241
Yeah, but your benefactors,
I can't seem to find any of them.

162
00:10:29,321 --> 00:10:32,401
Very simple reason for that.
I killed them all.

163
00:10:32,761 --> 00:10:35,401
-Buried them in my backyard.
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

164
00:10:35,681 --> 00:10:37,161
How big is your backyard, Mr Brock?

165
00:10:37,281 --> 00:10:40,321
-At the last count, Wyoming.
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

166
00:10:40,401 --> 00:10:41,561
(CAMERAS CLICKING)

167
00:10:41,681 --> 00:10:44,121
Now, if you good people will excuse me,

168
00:10:44,201 --> 00:10:46,081
this young lady will guide you
to the exit.

169
00:10:46,161 --> 00:10:49,161
MAN: Mr Brock... Uh, Mr Brock.

170
00:10:49,441 --> 00:10:50,681
Mr Brock? Mr Brock?

171
00:10:50,761 --> 00:10:52,321
Apparently, we have one more question.

172
00:10:52,401 --> 00:10:54,241
Yes. Uh, where is the little boys' room?

173
00:10:56,841 --> 00:11:00,441
I think you'll find the restrooms
to the left on your way out.

174
00:11:00,641 --> 00:11:03,241
No, not the restrooms,
the little boys' room.

175
00:11:03,361 --> 00:11:04,801
If you successfully
locate the restrooms,

176
00:11:04,881 --> 00:11:06,441
I think you'll find
everything you need in there.

177
00:11:06,881 --> 00:11:09,121
-Thank you, all.
-WOMAN: This way, ladies and gentlemen.

178
00:11:10,241 --> 00:11:11,681
I don't wanna rest.

179
00:11:11,761 --> 00:11:14,321
If I was just having a rest,
I might cause an incident.

180
00:11:14,401 --> 00:11:16,041
(PEOPLE MURMURING)

181
00:11:19,681 --> 00:11:21,881
Dr Sim, is there a problem?

182
00:11:24,041 --> 00:11:27,121
It's the brains.
There's something I need to show you.

183
00:11:27,801 --> 00:11:29,041
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

184
00:11:29,121 --> 00:11:30,401
DR SIM: It's necessary.
MR BROCK: Later.

185
00:11:31,281 --> 00:11:33,441
Meet me here. Midnight.

186
00:11:34,441 --> 00:11:35,721
Thank you, sir.

187
00:11:50,081 --> 00:11:53,161
(SIGHS) Mr Brock. You startled me.

188
00:11:53,241 --> 00:11:54,681
Shall we?

189
00:11:55,761 --> 00:11:57,081
Of course.

190
00:12:22,241 --> 00:12:23,721
(WHISPERS) All clear.

191
00:12:30,441 --> 00:12:31,561
(DOOR OPENS)

192
00:12:42,881 --> 00:12:45,241
-Well?
-Look at them.

193
00:12:45,721 --> 00:12:46,841
You see nothing unusual?

194
00:12:47,121 --> 00:12:50,681
I see brains, every place except here.

195
00:12:55,521 --> 00:12:58,521
MR BROCK: These specimens were donated
to this facility by our benefactors

196
00:12:58,601 --> 00:13:00,721
for a top secret research project.

197
00:13:00,801 --> 00:13:03,321
A project which is not to be questioned,
impeded, or in fact,

198
00:13:03,401 --> 00:13:07,561
mentioned by any of the employees
at the Harmony Shoal institute.

199
00:13:07,681 --> 00:13:10,961
Even I don't have the clearance
to know what's going on in here.

200
00:13:11,041 --> 00:13:13,561
-DR SIM: But why?
-Is that your job to ask questions?

201
00:13:13,681 --> 00:13:15,561
Stick to science.

202
00:13:18,241 --> 00:13:19,601
Something wrong with your eyes?

203
00:13:20,321 --> 00:13:23,761
Sir, the first time I came in here,
I counted 24 specimens.

204
00:13:24,241 --> 00:13:26,321
The second time I counted,
there were 30.

205
00:13:26,401 --> 00:13:27,521
Now, there are 36.

206
00:13:27,601 --> 00:13:30,321
-Well, I guess they got the space.
-You don't understand.

207
00:13:30,401 --> 00:13:32,001
There have been no deliveries.
I checked it.

208
00:13:33,441 --> 00:13:35,841
Some of these brains, sir, they just...

209
00:13:37,281 --> 00:13:38,721
Arrived.

210
00:13:43,681 --> 00:13:45,041
(GASPS SOFTLY)

211
00:13:54,121 --> 00:13:56,281
It's okay. I'm an intruder, too.

212
00:14:00,521 --> 00:14:04,401
Yeah, I brought snacks.
Mark of a pro. Keep listening.

213
00:14:08,521 --> 00:14:10,081
MR BROCK: It looks like a brain to me.

214
00:14:11,641 --> 00:14:13,921
Kind of blue, I guess,
but that's the fluid, right?

215
00:14:14,001 --> 00:14:16,281
DR SIM: Yes, that's the fluid.

216
00:14:16,361 --> 00:14:17,881
Tap the glass, sir.

217
00:14:18,801 --> 00:14:20,521
(CHUCKLING) What'd you say?

218
00:14:20,601 --> 00:14:22,121
Tap the glass, please.

219
00:14:32,041 --> 00:14:34,921
MR BROCK: What? What the hell is that?

220
00:14:36,241 --> 00:14:37,281
Is that a joke?

221
00:14:37,361 --> 00:14:39,321
No, sir, it's not a joke.

222
00:14:39,401 --> 00:14:41,841
It's got eyes. Look at them.
They're like...

223
00:14:46,601 --> 00:14:47,761
They're like your eyes.

224
00:14:51,281 --> 00:14:53,361
Yes, sir. They are.

225
00:15:00,761 --> 00:15:01,801
MR BROCK: Dr Sim!

226
00:15:05,361 --> 00:15:07,601
-What are you pointing at?
-I'm pointing at Dr Sim.

227
00:15:10,241 --> 00:15:11,881
Don't look so alarmed.

228
00:15:12,001 --> 00:15:14,041
We merely exchanged containers.

229
00:15:14,801 --> 00:15:17,961
You might call this a hijack.

230
00:15:18,681 --> 00:15:19,881
(GRUNTS)

231
00:15:20,481 --> 00:15:22,841
(CHOKING)

232
00:15:24,481 --> 00:15:25,681
(GASPS)

233
00:15:30,041 --> 00:15:32,441
What happened to you?
I don't understand.

234
00:15:33,801 --> 00:15:35,681
The same thing
that is about to happen to you.

235
00:15:35,761 --> 00:15:38,081
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

236
00:15:43,481 --> 00:15:45,201
I had a change of mind.

237
00:15:46,361 --> 00:15:48,041
(DOORS OPENING)

238
00:15:58,681 --> 00:16:00,401
MR BROCK: No. Please. No.

239
00:16:03,681 --> 00:16:05,161
Let me out of here!

240
00:16:06,441 --> 00:16:09,201
What's happening?
(STRUGGLING) What are you doing?

241
00:16:10,201 --> 00:16:12,001
-(GRUNTS)
-(CONTAINER CREAKING)

242
00:16:22,001 --> 00:16:23,361
(LOCK ENGAGES)

243
00:16:44,401 --> 00:16:45,681
Who are you?

244
00:16:45,761 --> 00:16:47,681
Lucy Fletcher,
reporter from the Daily Chronicle.

245
00:16:47,761 --> 00:16:50,401
Hang on, why am I telling you the truth?

246
00:16:50,481 --> 00:16:52,881
-Spooky, isn't it? Looking for a story?
-I think I just found one.

247
00:16:52,961 --> 00:16:54,041
"Brains with minds of their own."

248
00:16:54,121 --> 00:16:56,161
No one will believe that.
This is America.

249
00:16:56,241 --> 00:16:57,281
Who are you?

250
00:16:57,361 --> 00:17:00,001
Special agent Damn Dangerous
from Scotland Yard, Scotland,

251
00:17:00,081 --> 00:17:01,321
the Doctor, for short.

252
00:17:01,401 --> 00:17:04,041
See, they've got institutes
all over the world.

253
00:17:04,121 --> 00:17:06,361
They're always in capital cities.

254
00:17:06,721 --> 00:17:09,361
-Nope.
-Yes.

255
00:17:09,601 --> 00:17:11,401
Yes, they are. See?

256
00:17:11,601 --> 00:17:13,521
New York's not capital city, is it?

257
00:17:13,601 --> 00:17:15,641
You don't need to point out mistakes.
That's not what you're for.

258
00:17:15,721 --> 00:17:17,801
-Washington's got its own one, yeah.
-(LIGHT SWITCH CLANKS)

259
00:17:20,041 --> 00:17:24,121
I would call security,
but they might leave you alive.

260
00:17:24,961 --> 00:17:28,721
I do not want any awkward questions
about the intruders

261
00:17:28,801 --> 00:17:31,121
I was forced to shoot
for my own protection.

262
00:17:31,241 --> 00:17:32,401
(CHUCKLES)

263
00:17:32,761 --> 00:17:33,841
DOCTOR: Good plan.

264
00:17:34,321 --> 00:17:36,521
Here's another one. Go on.

265
00:17:37,441 --> 00:17:39,921
Tell them you shot us in the back
in self-defence.

266
00:17:40,801 --> 00:17:42,921
We'll be laughing
all the way to the slab.

267
00:17:44,121 --> 00:17:45,921
-Face me.
-Maybe not.

268
00:17:46,281 --> 00:17:47,401
Face me now.

269
00:17:47,481 --> 00:17:49,961
-(THUDDING)
-What is that?

270
00:17:50,121 --> 00:17:51,481
-It's not me.
-LUCY: It sounds like...

271
00:17:51,601 --> 00:17:52,681
(KNOCKING)

272
00:17:52,761 --> 00:17:55,361
-Like someone knocking at a window.
-We're on the 100th floor.

273
00:17:55,521 --> 00:17:56,961
(KNOCKING CONTINUES)

274
00:18:06,321 --> 00:18:07,521
Oh, my God. He's real.

275
00:18:07,601 --> 00:18:09,361
-DOCTOR: Who's real?
-The Ghost.

276
00:18:09,441 --> 00:18:10,521
DOCTOR: Who's the Ghost?

277
00:18:10,601 --> 00:18:12,401
-LUCY: Masked vigilante, but he's...
-What?

278
00:18:13,161 --> 00:18:14,201
Super.

279
00:18:14,841 --> 00:18:16,801
-(SNAPS FINGERS)
-(SHATTERS)

280
00:18:25,721 --> 00:18:26,801
Mind if I come in?

281
00:18:27,601 --> 00:18:28,761
Impressive.

282
00:18:29,201 --> 00:18:31,161
Those windows,
like everything in this building,

283
00:18:31,241 --> 00:18:33,281
are built to withstand a blast

284
00:18:33,361 --> 00:18:35,401
equivalent to four nuclear explosions.

285
00:18:35,481 --> 00:18:37,521
Sorry about that.
Would you like me to call a glazier?

286
00:18:37,961 --> 00:18:39,161
Hmm.

287
00:18:45,241 --> 00:18:47,041
(GUN CLICKING)

288
00:18:53,801 --> 00:18:54,881
(GASPS)

289
00:18:55,041 --> 00:18:56,921
Please understand that
it's against my personal code

290
00:18:57,001 --> 00:18:59,001
to cause lasting harm to any individual.

291
00:18:59,361 --> 00:19:00,721
(GROANS)

292
00:19:01,641 --> 00:19:04,121
However, light to
moderate injury is fine.

293
00:19:05,281 --> 00:19:07,041
-That was good.
-GHOST: Hello.

294
00:19:07,521 --> 00:19:10,281
-Was that man annoying you?
-LUCY: You're real?

295
00:19:11,041 --> 00:19:13,881
I can't believe that you're ac...
Actually real.

296
00:19:13,961 --> 00:19:16,841
I'm afraid I am.
I enjoy your column, Miss Fletcher.

297
00:19:16,921 --> 00:19:18,241
You read my column? You read?

298
00:19:18,961 --> 00:19:19,961
You're real and you read?

299
00:19:20,041 --> 00:19:21,081
Though I find the political bias

300
00:19:21,161 --> 00:19:22,921
in your paper's editorial
not entirely to my taste.

301
00:19:23,001 --> 00:19:24,321
-I'll pass that on.
-Thank you.

302
00:19:24,401 --> 00:19:26,521
-And who are these gentlemen?
-They're, erm...

303
00:19:27,761 --> 00:19:28,801
I don't actually know.

304
00:19:28,881 --> 00:19:31,761
-Uh, this is my friend, Nardole.
-Hello, Ghost.

305
00:19:32,081 --> 00:19:33,441
And I'm the Doctor.

306
00:19:34,401 --> 00:19:35,681
The Doctor?

307
00:19:36,481 --> 00:19:37,921
I thought we had lots of doctors.

308
00:19:39,041 --> 00:19:40,361
I'm the main one.

309
00:19:43,721 --> 00:19:45,361
-Can I give you a ride home?
-You have a car?

310
00:19:45,441 --> 00:19:47,801
-No.
-(GASPS)

311
00:19:48,521 --> 00:19:51,041
-I hope you're okay with heights.
-I'm okay so far.

312
00:19:54,121 --> 00:19:55,921
Have a good evening, gentlemen.

313
00:19:56,281 --> 00:19:57,321
(LUCY SCREAMS)

314
00:20:02,721 --> 00:20:04,241
This seems nice.

315
00:20:07,241 --> 00:20:08,841
Grant.

316
00:20:08,921 --> 00:20:10,801
YOUNG GRANT: So, I'm a superhero now?

317
00:20:11,361 --> 00:20:13,721
DOCTOR: Well, once the gemstone
is gone from inside you,

318
00:20:13,801 --> 00:20:15,761
you'll be back to normal.

319
00:20:15,841 --> 00:20:18,401
-It will pass.
-But how will it get out?

320
00:20:18,481 --> 00:20:20,681
Uh, like I said, it will pass.

321
00:20:21,361 --> 00:20:23,321
-Looking forward to that.
-Are you sure?

322
00:20:23,681 --> 00:20:26,001
Of course I'm not sure.
Nothing's ever sure.

323
00:20:27,881 --> 00:20:29,081
Just promise me one thing.

324
00:20:29,601 --> 00:20:32,201
For as long as you have these powers,

325
00:20:32,281 --> 00:20:35,601
you will never ever use them.

326
00:20:38,841 --> 00:20:40,081
Sure.

327
00:20:45,721 --> 00:20:47,521
-Is this the right building?
-(GASPS)

328
00:20:47,601 --> 00:20:49,601
They all look the same from up there.

329
00:20:50,401 --> 00:20:51,721
Uh, yeah.

330
00:20:51,961 --> 00:20:53,641
Yeah, this is me. Thanks.

331
00:20:53,721 --> 00:20:55,961
Well, I certainly hope
this unpleasant experience

332
00:20:56,041 --> 00:20:57,881
hasn't put you off
your career in journalism.

333
00:20:58,361 --> 00:20:59,961
Oh, no. No, no. Not at all.

334
00:21:00,041 --> 00:21:02,641
(BEEPING)

335
00:21:02,721 --> 00:21:04,521
Sorry, duty calls.

336
00:21:04,601 --> 00:21:07,081
Look at that.
The bat signal's an app now?

337
00:21:07,441 --> 00:21:09,281
What is it? Bank robbery, hijack?

338
00:21:09,481 --> 00:21:11,841
Uh... Something like that.

339
00:21:12,801 --> 00:21:14,241
Excuse me.

340
00:21:17,681 --> 00:21:19,001
Go get 'em.

341
00:21:22,321 --> 00:21:24,441
(BABY CRYING)

342
00:21:28,481 --> 00:21:30,041
(PANTING)

343
00:21:31,721 --> 00:21:34,121
With great power
comes great responsibility.

344
00:21:34,841 --> 00:21:36,201
(EXHALES)

345
00:21:36,281 --> 00:21:38,561
No man worthy of a title

346
00:21:39,481 --> 00:21:41,001
leaves a baby alone.

347
00:21:41,441 --> 00:21:44,641
-How'd you find me?
-I tracked the gemstone inside you.

348
00:21:46,841 --> 00:21:48,281
(GRANT STAMMERS)

349
00:21:48,641 --> 00:21:51,401
DOCTOR: Your powers,
they don't belong in this world.

350
00:21:51,481 --> 00:21:52,961
They're an anomaly.

351
00:21:53,041 --> 00:21:55,641
-You promised me you'd never use them.
-May I take her?

352
00:21:56,801 --> 00:21:59,961
-She's yours?
-Uh, I'm hers. I'm her nanny.

353
00:22:00,921 --> 00:22:02,241
You're her nanny?

354
00:22:02,881 --> 00:22:04,641
Yeah, her nanny.
You got a problem with that?

355
00:22:04,721 --> 00:22:07,001
No. No, it's just... (STAMMERS)

356
00:22:07,081 --> 00:22:09,321
Okay, so you are a superhero
and a nanny?

357
00:22:09,441 --> 00:22:10,721
Well, you got to make a buck somehow.

358
00:22:10,801 --> 00:22:12,361
I mean, you don't get paid
for saving people.

359
00:22:12,441 --> 00:22:15,201
Oh, you don't have to tell us.
Here you go.

360
00:22:15,281 --> 00:22:18,641
Nice and warm and tasty. Ooh, elephant.

361
00:22:19,681 --> 00:22:22,281
I mean, it's fine.
It's a long range baby monitor.

362
00:22:22,841 --> 00:22:24,281
-(TOY SQUEAKING)
-I can get back to this apartment

363
00:22:24,361 --> 00:22:27,521
quicker than most people can get
to their kid's bedrooms.

364
00:22:27,601 --> 00:22:29,961
Grant. Grant, this is insane.

365
00:22:30,041 --> 00:22:32,241
Look, I'm me, the Doctor.

366
00:22:32,361 --> 00:22:34,321
-And even I think this is insane.
-Even him?

367
00:22:34,401 --> 00:22:35,521
I can cope.

368
00:22:35,641 --> 00:22:37,681
Of course, you can't.
When do you sleep?

369
00:22:38,401 --> 00:22:40,561
-When are you not on call?
-(DOOR OPENS)

370
00:22:40,641 --> 00:22:42,721
How complicated
do you need your life to be?

371
00:22:42,801 --> 00:22:44,481
-(DOOR CLOSES)
-Well,

372
00:22:44,561 --> 00:22:46,561
not as complicated as it's about to get.

373
00:22:47,481 --> 00:22:50,321
-Uh, we're in here, Mrs Lombard.
-MRS LOMBARD: Oh, Jennifer.

374
00:22:50,441 --> 00:22:52,241
Look at you. Up again?

375
00:22:52,721 --> 00:22:54,041
Don't you ever sleep?

376
00:22:54,121 --> 00:22:55,561
GRANT: Did you have a good evening,
Mrs Lombard?

377
00:22:55,641 --> 00:22:58,441
MRS LOMBARD: Oh, well, it was work.
Why would it be good?

378
00:22:58,521 --> 00:23:02,681
GRANT: Uh... Well, erm, I don't know,
you seem a little buzzed.

379
00:23:02,761 --> 00:23:05,681
-I thought maybe you met someone.
-Maybe I did, maybe I didn't.

380
00:23:05,761 --> 00:23:07,361
-Uh... Grant, what...
-(SIGHS)

381
00:23:08,561 --> 00:23:10,361
What are you doing here?

382
00:23:10,441 --> 00:23:12,081
We could ask you the same question.

383
00:23:12,161 --> 00:23:14,241
But it's your apartment,
so we probably won't.

384
00:23:14,361 --> 00:23:15,521
Well...

385
00:23:16,521 --> 00:23:17,601
(BABY COOING)

386
00:23:19,121 --> 00:23:21,641
(STAMMERS) We were worried about you.

387
00:23:22,041 --> 00:23:24,521
We wanted to make sure that
you were all right,

388
00:23:24,601 --> 00:23:26,401
so, uh, we followed you.

389
00:23:26,481 --> 00:23:28,201
You followed me and got here first?

390
00:23:28,281 --> 00:23:30,361
Well, that's just a measure
of our concern.

391
00:23:30,441 --> 00:23:33,081
-Very concerned.
-They said they knew you. I let them in.

392
00:23:33,201 --> 00:23:34,601
Oh, we met tonight.

393
00:23:35,401 --> 00:23:36,921
We need to talk, you and me.

394
00:23:37,641 --> 00:23:39,521
GRANT: Oh! Did something happen?

395
00:23:39,641 --> 00:23:40,721
(TOY SQUEAKS)

396
00:23:40,801 --> 00:23:43,241
Nothing for you to worry
your pretty little head about.

397
00:23:44,281 --> 00:23:45,601
I'll put her to bed.

398
00:23:45,681 --> 00:23:48,201
-I can do that.
-No, no, it's okay. I want to.

399
00:23:54,961 --> 00:23:57,121
Lombard's her married name.

400
00:23:58,681 --> 00:24:02,561
He ran off when the baby came along.

401
00:24:03,801 --> 00:24:05,041
Lucy.

402
00:24:06,761 --> 00:24:08,121
Of course.

403
00:24:08,321 --> 00:24:10,241
-(BELL RINGING)
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

404
00:24:15,281 --> 00:24:17,921
-Hey.
-What are you doing here?

405
00:24:18,481 --> 00:24:21,281
I'm your relief algebra teacher.
Thought I'd check in on you,

406
00:24:21,361 --> 00:24:22,401
and see how you're coping.

407
00:24:22,481 --> 00:24:24,961
Well, it hasn't passed,
if that's what you wanna know.

408
00:24:26,481 --> 00:24:28,561
I think that
it's a part of your DNA now.

409
00:24:29,161 --> 00:24:30,521
It's bonded with you.

410
00:24:31,321 --> 00:24:32,961
I'm sorry.

411
00:24:37,841 --> 00:24:40,281
-Why aren't you looking at me?
-I don't want to.

412
00:24:40,361 --> 00:24:42,681
You're not looking at anyone.
Are you shy now?

413
00:24:44,041 --> 00:24:45,521
Is that floor really interesting?

414
00:24:45,601 --> 00:24:48,001
I'm not shy. I just can't stop it.

415
00:24:48,521 --> 00:24:50,881
-Can't stop what?
-The X-ray vision.

416
00:24:53,961 --> 00:24:55,081
Oh.

417
00:24:55,801 --> 00:24:57,881
TEEN GRANT: I'm in hell, naked hell.

418
00:24:57,961 --> 00:24:59,921
I just can't look at people.

419
00:25:00,041 --> 00:25:04,641
It's the gemstone responding to puberty.

420
00:25:05,201 --> 00:25:07,321
-Hey, Grant.
-Hey, Lucy.

421
00:25:07,401 --> 00:25:08,601
(GIRLS LAUGHING)

422
00:25:09,521 --> 00:25:10,801
You really like her, don't you?

423
00:25:10,881 --> 00:25:12,921
I have X-ray eyes. I like everyone.

424
00:25:13,281 --> 00:25:15,401
But Lucy is your favourite?

425
00:25:15,481 --> 00:25:16,721
Who says?

426
00:25:21,041 --> 00:25:23,641
GRANT: A couple of years after
high school, I ran into her again.

427
00:25:23,721 --> 00:25:26,081
-She remembered me.
-DOCTOR: Ooh, that was lucky.

428
00:25:26,321 --> 00:25:28,561
And I was with my best friend
at the time,

429
00:25:29,041 --> 00:25:30,961
and she couldn't take her eyes off him.

430
00:25:31,481 --> 00:25:33,281
-Okay.
-Love at first sight.

431
00:25:33,801 --> 00:25:37,241
-Right.
-Then marriage, then a baby.

432
00:25:38,761 --> 00:25:40,961
And then he ran off with someone else.

433
00:25:41,081 --> 00:25:44,001
Leaving, I suppose,
a field open for you to move in.

434
00:25:44,081 --> 00:25:45,121
Yeah.

435
00:25:45,201 --> 00:25:47,241
And care for the child she'd had
by another man?

436
00:25:47,321 --> 00:25:48,521
Yeah.

437
00:25:48,601 --> 00:25:51,321
So she could keep working and
possibly date other friends of yours?

438
00:25:52,121 --> 00:25:54,001
-Pretty much.
-You tiger!

439
00:25:55,641 --> 00:25:58,521
-Thank you!
-Who are you thanking?

440
00:25:58,801 --> 00:26:01,401
The universe.
Somebody once said this to me.

441
00:26:01,481 --> 00:26:03,321
(SIRENS BLARING)

442
00:26:06,361 --> 00:26:07,561
(HORNS HONKING)

443
00:26:12,641 --> 00:26:13,921
Excuse me.

444
00:26:14,001 --> 00:26:15,001
(WHOOSHES)

445
00:26:30,881 --> 00:26:32,361
(TOY SQUEAKS)

446
00:26:32,441 --> 00:26:33,681
This is Mr Huffle.

447
00:26:34,241 --> 00:26:35,881
Mr Huffle feels pain.

448
00:26:35,961 --> 00:26:37,601
(TOY SQUEAKING)

449
00:26:38,041 --> 00:26:40,001
-Meet me in the kitchen.
-(TOY SQUEAKS)

450
00:26:40,761 --> 00:26:42,761
(SIGHING)

451
00:26:43,321 --> 00:26:45,521
(REPORTER SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY ON TV)

452
00:26:57,801 --> 00:26:59,601
-With you in a minute.
-(TYPING)

453
00:27:08,881 --> 00:27:12,641
-So, you're from Scotland Yard?
-Yes.

454
00:27:12,801 --> 00:27:14,161
(TOY SQUEAKING)

455
00:27:16,681 --> 00:27:18,361
It's fine if you don't tell me
your secrets.

456
00:27:18,441 --> 00:27:20,201
I intend to keep mine,
but don't lie to me.

457
00:27:20,521 --> 00:27:22,161
-Or what?
-I hurt Mr Huffle.

458
00:27:23,161 --> 00:27:24,561
(TOY SQUEAKING)

459
00:27:24,641 --> 00:27:28,761
I assume you belong to
some kind of, I don't know, agency,

460
00:27:28,841 --> 00:27:30,441
I don't care which one.

461
00:27:30,521 --> 00:27:34,041
And that your current assignment is to
investigate Harmony Shoal, correct?

462
00:27:34,121 --> 00:27:36,081
-No, I was just passing...
-(TOY SQUEAKS)

463
00:27:36,161 --> 00:27:39,881
Okay, okay. Yes, fine.
Okay, yes. Broadly speaking, yes.

464
00:27:39,961 --> 00:27:41,401
(TOY CONTINUES SQUEAKING)

465
00:27:41,481 --> 00:27:42,961
What are those brain things?

466
00:27:44,241 --> 00:27:45,321
-I don't know.
-(TOY SQUEAKING)

467
00:27:45,401 --> 00:27:46,641
It's nothing that need concern you.

468
00:27:46,721 --> 00:27:49,601
I'm a reporter.
That category does not exist.

469
00:27:49,681 --> 00:27:50,761
What are they?

470
00:27:51,881 --> 00:27:53,161
Well, you wouldn't believe me
if I told you.

471
00:27:53,241 --> 00:27:54,921
No reason not to tell me then.

472
00:27:55,001 --> 00:27:57,081
(TOY SQUEAKING)

473
00:27:58,881 --> 00:28:02,441
Those brains, they aren't just brains.

474
00:28:04,001 --> 00:28:05,881
They're independent alien life forms.

475
00:28:06,921 --> 00:28:08,161
And?

476
00:28:08,401 --> 00:28:10,041
(TOY SQUEAKING)

477
00:28:11,201 --> 00:28:13,201
They migrate from planet to planet,

478
00:28:13,721 --> 00:28:17,001
extracting and replacing
the central nervous systems

479
00:28:17,081 --> 00:28:18,321
of compatible hosts.

480
00:28:18,401 --> 00:28:19,401
And?

481
00:28:21,201 --> 00:28:23,521
Harmony Shoal
Is a multinational corporation

482
00:28:23,601 --> 00:28:27,681
whose true purpose is to extract
and replace the brains

483
00:28:27,761 --> 00:28:30,161
of key authority figures
from around the world

484
00:28:30,241 --> 00:28:33,841
and prepare Earth for full colonisation.

485
00:28:34,241 --> 00:28:35,241
(TOY SQUEAKS)

486
00:28:37,201 --> 00:28:40,001
-Huh.
-You believe me?

487
00:28:40,601 --> 00:28:42,761
I don't think you're lying.
Slightly different.

488
00:28:44,081 --> 00:28:46,481
What has Harmony Shoal
got to do with the Ghost?

489
00:28:46,841 --> 00:28:47,881
Nothing.

490
00:28:47,961 --> 00:28:50,001
Ah. So you know
who the Ghost really is, then.

491
00:28:50,081 --> 00:28:51,201
No, I have no idea...

492
00:28:51,281 --> 00:28:52,321
-Oh, stop it!
-(TOY SQUEAKS)

493
00:28:52,401 --> 00:28:54,121
We just went to a top secret science
research facility,

494
00:28:54,201 --> 00:28:55,681
apparently run by brains from space,

495
00:28:55,761 --> 00:28:57,881
and a flying man
with super powers turns up.

496
00:28:58,041 --> 00:28:59,641
Anybody would assume
that you're connected,

497
00:28:59,721 --> 00:29:01,681
except for somebody
who already knew they weren't.

498
00:29:01,761 --> 00:29:03,921
So, clearly you know the Ghost
and trust him.

499
00:29:04,001 --> 00:29:06,001
Nobody trusts anybody
without knowing who they are.

500
00:29:06,081 --> 00:29:07,401
So you know who he really is.

501
00:29:07,481 --> 00:29:09,201
So now you can tell me.
Who is he?

502
00:29:11,121 --> 00:29:12,121
Oh, that's interesting.

503
00:29:12,561 --> 00:29:13,921
You don't work for an agency, do you?

504
00:29:14,561 --> 00:29:15,561
Don't I?

505
00:29:15,641 --> 00:29:17,161
You're not used to being spoken
to you like this,

506
00:29:17,241 --> 00:29:19,241
which means you don't have
a boss or an employer.

507
00:29:19,321 --> 00:29:21,161
So why are you
investigating Harmony Shoal?

508
00:29:21,241 --> 00:29:22,721
-What's in it for you?
-I like to keep busy.

509
00:29:22,801 --> 00:29:24,521
-Why? What happened to you?
-Nothing.

510
00:29:24,601 --> 00:29:25,921
-Oh, look!
-(TOY SQUEAKS)

511
00:29:28,161 --> 00:29:29,761
-(SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY)
-LUCY: Whoa.

512
00:29:30,361 --> 00:29:34,641
...because fire prevention is
the responsibility of every citizen.

513
00:29:35,201 --> 00:29:38,041
-So, get a smoke detector!
-(BABY CRIES)

514
00:29:38,121 --> 00:29:40,441
-(BABY MONITOR BEEPS)
-Sorry, duty calls.

515
00:29:41,481 --> 00:29:42,681
LUCY: Oh, look at him go.

516
00:29:43,681 --> 00:29:44,921
I need to know who he is.

517
00:29:45,001 --> 00:29:47,721
Oh, you're all right.
She just needs a change.

518
00:29:47,801 --> 00:29:49,321
It's okay. I'll do it.

519
00:29:49,761 --> 00:29:52,201
-You're so quick, Grant.
-Oh, yes. He's definitely quick.

520
00:29:55,681 --> 00:29:58,081
-Do you have any time off?
-Sure.

521
00:29:58,721 --> 00:30:02,921
...it became clear that two children
were still trapped on the big wheel.

522
00:30:03,041 --> 00:30:04,761
- The two small figures,
-(WHOOSHING)

523
00:30:04,841 --> 00:30:07,001
As you can see are clinging on to the...

524
00:30:09,561 --> 00:30:10,841
LUCY: Doctor?

525
00:30:13,801 --> 00:30:15,921
So, can you put me in touch with him?

526
00:30:16,001 --> 00:30:18,041
-(SIGHS)
-The real guy behind the mask?

527
00:30:19,321 --> 00:30:20,561
You're smart.

528
00:30:20,641 --> 00:30:22,241
(WHISPERS) You're so clever
I actually noticed,

529
00:30:22,321 --> 00:30:24,121
and I hardly ever listen
when other people are talking.

530
00:30:24,201 --> 00:30:27,201
-So what?
-So why can't you find him yourself?

531
00:30:27,281 --> 00:30:29,641
-I got a lead.
-What lead?

532
00:30:30,201 --> 00:30:33,041
You. You know him.
Don't even try telling me you don't.

533
00:30:33,121 --> 00:30:34,761
Well, maybe you know him too?

534
00:30:36,481 --> 00:30:39,401
-Hey, where did Grant go?
-Right here, Mrs Lombard.

535
00:30:39,481 --> 00:30:40,881
-Oh.
-Would you like your coffee?

536
00:30:41,201 --> 00:30:43,041
Oh, no. I'm okay, thanks.

537
00:30:43,881 --> 00:30:45,401
-LUCY: Are you all right?
-Sure, why?

538
00:30:45,841 --> 00:30:48,521
-You're kind of wet.
-I prefer mild-mannered.

539
00:30:48,641 --> 00:30:51,041
(INHALES SHARPLY)
Can you put me in touch with him?

540
00:30:53,161 --> 00:30:55,601
-The Ghost?
-Yeah. The Ghost.

541
00:30:56,961 --> 00:30:58,121
Mrs Lombard,

542
00:30:58,841 --> 00:31:03,841
there are some situations which are just
too stupid to be allowed to continue.

543
00:31:03,921 --> 00:31:05,161
-(MOBILE RINGS)
-(DOCTOR SIGHS)

544
00:31:05,241 --> 00:31:06,521
Hang on.

545
00:31:08,321 --> 00:31:10,241
-Hello?
-MAN: Is this Lucy Fletcher?

546
00:31:10,321 --> 00:31:12,361
-Yes, who is this?
-Sorry, I had to fly.

547
00:31:12,441 --> 00:31:16,841
(GASPS) Am I? Sorry.
Am I speaking to the Ghost?

548
00:31:18,241 --> 00:31:19,641
Hello, Lucy.

549
00:31:20,601 --> 00:31:24,961
So, I'm hoping this means
I'm getting an interview?

550
00:31:25,721 --> 00:31:28,441
An interview is entirely possible.

551
00:31:28,801 --> 00:31:31,321
(IN A GRUFF VOICE)
But I must make one thing clear,

552
00:31:31,401 --> 00:31:34,641
there must be no talk
of who I really am.

553
00:31:35,001 --> 00:31:37,961
Hey, you make the headlines,
you make the rules.

554
00:31:38,121 --> 00:31:42,441
Discussion of my true identity would
put the people closest to me at risk.

555
00:31:42,641 --> 00:31:45,601
-That is not acceptable.
-Fair enough. Get that.

556
00:31:46,241 --> 00:31:47,801
How about tomorrow night?

557
00:31:48,601 --> 00:31:49,721
For what?

558
00:31:51,001 --> 00:31:53,401
The interview? We could get dinner.

559
00:31:53,841 --> 00:31:56,201
-Dinner?
-Do you eat dinner?

560
00:31:57,641 --> 00:31:59,761
-Of course I eat dinner.
-Okay then.

561
00:32:00,241 --> 00:32:04,001
Pick me up here,
tomorrow night, erm, 8:00.

562
00:32:04,081 --> 00:32:05,681
I'll wait for you on the roof?

563
00:32:05,761 --> 00:32:07,081
(LUCY COOS AND GASPS)

564
00:32:07,441 --> 00:32:08,561
Wait a second.

565
00:32:12,721 --> 00:32:14,801
Grant, could you babysit for me
tomorrow night?

566
00:32:14,921 --> 00:32:17,241
-(IN NORMAL VOICE) Erm...
-Please, it's important.

567
00:32:18,241 --> 00:32:19,481
BOTH: I've got a date.

568
00:32:19,881 --> 00:32:20,961
BOTH: A date?

569
00:32:21,601 --> 00:32:23,401
-Uh, kind of a date.
-Okay.

570
00:32:23,481 --> 00:32:24,721
An interview.

571
00:32:26,761 --> 00:32:29,561
-Are you seeing someone?
-Erm...

572
00:32:30,401 --> 00:32:32,121
None of my business. I mean...

573
00:32:33,041 --> 00:32:34,321
But are you?

574
00:32:34,401 --> 00:32:37,361
I mean, you never even go out
and suddenly you got a date?

575
00:32:37,441 --> 00:32:39,921
Yeah, well, it kind of came
as a surprise to me too.

576
00:32:40,281 --> 00:32:41,681
-I'm sorry?
-It's complicated.

577
00:32:41,761 --> 00:32:43,841
I can confirm that.
It's definitely complicated.

578
00:32:45,121 --> 00:32:48,001
You know, don't worry about it.
I'll look after Jennifer.

579
00:32:48,081 --> 00:32:49,201
-You will?
-You will?

580
00:32:49,281 --> 00:32:51,641
I'll figure it out.
Let me take care of it.

581
00:32:51,721 --> 00:32:52,921
-Okay.
-Okay.

582
00:33:03,521 --> 00:33:05,161
-(WHISPERS) She's jealous.
-I'm jealous.

583
00:33:05,961 --> 00:33:07,361
Grant, you are jealous of you.

584
00:33:07,441 --> 00:33:09,001
Technically, she's jealous of her?

585
00:33:09,081 --> 00:33:10,801
Grant, how long have you
known this woman?

586
00:33:10,881 --> 00:33:13,721
Since elementary school? 24 years.

587
00:33:16,721 --> 00:33:18,121
Twenty-four years?

588
00:33:19,921 --> 00:33:21,801
Yeah, of course it would be then...

589
00:33:22,161 --> 00:33:23,441
You okay?

590
00:33:24,561 --> 00:33:27,081
Time passes for everyone, even for me.

591
00:33:27,161 --> 00:33:28,441
So, please,

592
00:33:28,521 --> 00:33:33,241
as much as it is possible for
a human male, try not to be an idiot.

593
00:33:33,641 --> 00:33:35,521
No, seriously, are you okay?

594
00:33:36,361 --> 00:33:37,801
I'm always okay.

595
00:33:42,441 --> 00:33:44,841
(SIRENS WAILING IN THE DISTANCE)

596
00:33:45,241 --> 00:33:46,441
(GROANS SLOWLY)

597
00:33:48,121 --> 00:33:49,561
(WHOOSHING)

598
00:33:49,641 --> 00:33:51,281
(KEYBOARD CLACKING)

599
00:34:08,521 --> 00:34:11,041
-Ah! Welcome, brother.
-(SIGHS)

600
00:34:13,081 --> 00:34:14,241
How's your vehicle?

601
00:34:14,321 --> 00:34:16,081
-(BONES CRACKING)
-A little cramped.

602
00:34:16,361 --> 00:34:17,801
It will relax with wear.

603
00:34:20,841 --> 00:34:23,121
-Observe this.
-(KEYBOARD CLACKS)

604
00:34:23,281 --> 00:34:26,041
DR SIM: The finest vehicle
this planet has to offer.

605
00:34:26,481 --> 00:34:28,801
MR BROCK: Interesting.
But, can it be acquired?

606
00:34:28,881 --> 00:34:30,441
DR SIM: A plan is being formulated.

607
00:34:31,761 --> 00:34:34,241
This one. Who is he?

608
00:34:34,721 --> 00:34:37,121
-(COMPUTER BEEPING)
-I'm not sure,

609
00:34:37,201 --> 00:34:38,801
but he may be dangerous.

610
00:34:39,281 --> 00:34:40,641
He doesn't look dangerous.

611
00:34:42,721 --> 00:34:43,761
Boo!

612
00:34:44,361 --> 00:34:47,561
I'm talking to you live! In person!

613
00:34:49,641 --> 00:34:51,401
You can jump back in your skins now.

614
00:34:51,481 --> 00:34:53,361
Except, of course,
they're not your skins, are they?

615
00:34:53,441 --> 00:34:55,561
-What do you want?
-Mercy.

616
00:34:55,641 --> 00:34:58,161
-We have none.
-It's not a request, it's an offer.

617
00:34:59,761 --> 00:35:01,161
I'll give you a head start.

618
00:35:01,961 --> 00:35:04,001
I'll close my eyes
and I'll count to ten.

619
00:35:04,081 --> 00:35:06,041
I will make no attempt to follow you.

620
00:35:06,121 --> 00:35:09,201
But, starting now,
all of you, everywhere,

621
00:35:09,321 --> 00:35:11,481
pack your bags and
get off of this planet.

622
00:35:11,561 --> 00:35:12,961
Are you declaring war on us?

623
00:35:13,041 --> 00:35:14,281
I am drawing a line.

624
00:35:14,361 --> 00:35:17,161
And I'm suggesting you step back from it
with awesome speed.

625
00:35:17,241 --> 00:35:18,481
Then war it is.

626
00:35:28,841 --> 00:35:33,321
Multi-nucleate organism
functioning as an infinitely adaptable,

627
00:35:33,401 --> 00:35:37,321
independently functioning
peripatetic central nervous system.

628
00:35:37,401 --> 00:35:39,601
Good to keep an open mind. (CHUCKLES)

629
00:35:40,721 --> 00:35:42,881
-Of course, it won't work.
-What won't work?

630
00:35:42,961 --> 00:35:45,041
Whatever it is.
Whatever you've got planned.

631
00:35:45,121 --> 00:35:48,401
Stating the obvious, you've set up
in every capital city in the world,

632
00:35:48,481 --> 00:35:53,241
so clearly, the plan is to unzip
the head of every world leader,

633
00:35:53,321 --> 00:35:54,841
pop yourselves inside.

634
00:35:54,921 --> 00:35:57,001
Of course, you can't just roll up
with a team of surgeons

635
00:35:57,081 --> 00:35:58,721
to the White House or to the Kremlin,

636
00:35:58,801 --> 00:36:02,361
because they've got big fences,
shouty people and cross dogs.

637
00:36:02,441 --> 00:36:04,401
They will come to us.
And they will come running.

638
00:36:04,481 --> 00:36:05,561
Oh.

639
00:36:06,361 --> 00:36:08,561
I very much doubt it. Take this!

640
00:36:10,001 --> 00:36:11,241
Yes, take that!

641
00:36:11,761 --> 00:36:12,881
MR BROCK: Who are you?

642
00:36:12,961 --> 00:36:15,441
There have been many attempts
to conquer the Earth, I've lost count.

643
00:36:16,041 --> 00:36:19,641
Not one of them has succeeded.
Not a single one.

644
00:36:20,321 --> 00:36:24,121
They all lost and burned, and ran.

645
00:36:26,241 --> 00:36:27,841
That's who I am.

646
00:36:29,041 --> 00:36:31,001
(WHISTLING)

647
00:36:31,241 --> 00:36:34,121
-What is this?
-(CONTINUES WHISTLING)

648
00:36:34,841 --> 00:36:37,001
It's a burger. I always bring a snack.

649
00:36:37,081 --> 00:36:39,241
I don't want it.
Oh, he's put me off my dinner.

650
00:36:40,161 --> 00:36:41,681
(WHOOSHING)

651
00:36:46,361 --> 00:36:50,401
-Very good. Right on target.
-Extraordinary to be honest.

652
00:36:50,481 --> 00:36:52,921
A few accidental stop-offs
along the way.

653
00:36:53,001 --> 00:36:55,961
-Where did you get the robes?
-Twelfth century Constantinople.

654
00:36:56,041 --> 00:36:59,201
I rode firmly but wisely.
Uh-uh-uh!

655
00:36:59,881 --> 00:37:02,961
-How did it go?
-Oh, you know, issued a warning,

656
00:37:03,041 --> 00:37:04,201
donated a burger.

657
00:37:04,281 --> 00:37:06,201
Next I'm stationed with the Ghost.
What have you got?

658
00:37:06,281 --> 00:37:07,281
The whole story!

659
00:37:07,361 --> 00:37:08,841
Fact me, baby.
It's why I reassembled you.

660
00:37:08,921 --> 00:37:11,001
No, sir, that's not the reason, is it?

661
00:37:11,441 --> 00:37:12,481
Oh, just get on with it.

662
00:37:12,561 --> 00:37:16,441
You cut me out of Hydroflax because
you were worried you'd be lonely.

663
00:37:16,521 --> 00:37:18,281
And we both know why, don't we?

664
00:37:18,361 --> 00:37:21,481
But, oh! Look at you,
avoiding the subject.

665
00:37:21,561 --> 00:37:23,801
I'm not avoiding anything.
I'm just trying to save a planet.

666
00:37:23,881 --> 00:37:27,241
Which is what you always do
when the conversation turns serious.

667
00:37:32,001 --> 00:37:34,041
(SIRENS BLARING IN THE DISTANCE)

668
00:37:38,961 --> 00:37:41,241
-(COOING)
-Good girl...

669
00:37:43,121 --> 00:37:44,681
GRANT: Mrs Lombard?

670
00:37:45,161 --> 00:37:46,881
You look nice.

671
00:37:46,961 --> 00:37:48,281
-You look surprised.
-No, no, no.

672
00:37:48,361 --> 00:37:53,081
It's just, well, normally you wear
the little red dress when you're, uh...

673
00:37:54,441 --> 00:37:56,201
This is business, Grant.

674
00:37:57,121 --> 00:37:58,241
Strictly business.

675
00:38:00,481 --> 00:38:01,561
So...

676
00:38:02,361 --> 00:38:04,001
-I won't be late.
-Okay.

677
00:38:35,761 --> 00:38:37,201
(DOOR OPENING)

678
00:38:38,841 --> 00:38:39,921
Hi.

679
00:38:44,401 --> 00:38:45,721
(IN A GRUFF VOICE) Hi.

680
00:38:45,921 --> 00:38:47,361
Is something wrong?

681
00:38:48,281 --> 00:38:49,521
You look nice.

682
00:38:49,601 --> 00:38:51,521
-You look surprised.
-I am.

683
00:38:51,921 --> 00:38:53,081
A little.

684
00:38:53,281 --> 00:38:55,761
He's not supposed to be using
those powers, he made a promise.

685
00:38:55,841 --> 00:38:57,961
Well, like the Time Lord
promise never to interfere

686
00:38:58,041 --> 00:39:00,281
in the affairs of
other peoples or planets?

687
00:39:00,601 --> 00:39:02,161
I glued your head back on.

688
00:39:02,241 --> 00:39:03,841
Should have a little bit more respect.

689
00:39:03,921 --> 00:39:05,481
-(BEEPS)
-Oh.

690
00:39:06,841 --> 00:39:08,041
Come on.

691
00:39:09,801 --> 00:39:12,321
-Where are we?
-Where we were, except not.

692
00:39:12,841 --> 00:39:15,161
-Oh... What?
-(DOOR OPENING)

693
00:39:15,921 --> 00:39:17,921
(PEOPLE SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

694
00:39:26,961 --> 00:39:30,001
-Oh, Tokyo branch?
-Yep!

695
00:39:30,841 --> 00:39:32,001
Bit empty, isn't it?

696
00:39:32,081 --> 00:39:35,601
Yes, I created a distraction.
I flooded downstairs with Pokemon.

697
00:39:36,441 --> 00:39:38,121
-You're not supposed to be here.
-I know, it's terrible.

698
00:39:38,201 --> 00:39:40,201
Sorry, I'm doing everything
I can to stop me. See that?

699
00:39:40,281 --> 00:39:41,401
NARDOLE: It's a signal, isn't it?

700
00:39:41,481 --> 00:39:43,441
It's a signal beaming into space.

701
00:39:43,521 --> 00:39:45,401
There's one from
the New York office, too.

702
00:39:46,441 --> 00:39:47,961
Something in low orbit.

703
00:39:48,841 --> 00:39:50,201
I did book a restaurant.

704
00:39:50,281 --> 00:39:54,121
I'm not comfortable in restaurants.

705
00:39:56,561 --> 00:39:58,441
I suppose you get a lot of stares
dressed like that.

706
00:39:58,521 --> 00:39:59,841
Right back at you.

707
00:40:01,401 --> 00:40:03,601
-You sure you're warm enough?
-Yeah.

708
00:40:05,761 --> 00:40:07,161
Okay, no. (CHUCKLES)

709
00:40:07,681 --> 00:40:08,921
-(SNAPS FINGERS)
-(GASPS)

710
00:40:09,241 --> 00:40:11,961
-Now?
-Yeah. Definitely.

711
00:40:13,121 --> 00:40:15,801
-Yep, low orbit.
-But you can't get a fix on it?

712
00:40:15,881 --> 00:40:18,841
-I'm trying. Their shield is too good.
-Why can't we track the signals?

713
00:40:18,921 --> 00:40:20,401
DOCTOR: Tracking them now.

714
00:40:22,361 --> 00:40:24,281
-Boom.
-(LAUGHS)

715
00:40:25,081 --> 00:40:27,081
So what powers do you have?

716
00:40:27,881 --> 00:40:30,081
Well, basic flying,

717
00:40:30,361 --> 00:40:31,961
basic super strength.

718
00:40:32,041 --> 00:40:34,201
-Basic X-ray vision?
-Yep.

719
00:40:36,081 --> 00:40:37,561
Is that ever tempting?

720
00:40:37,641 --> 00:40:40,041
-Adolescence was difficult.
-In what sense?

721
00:40:40,281 --> 00:40:42,681
-It went on a lot longer.
-How much longer?

722
00:40:43,521 --> 00:40:44,801
I'll let you know.

723
00:40:45,001 --> 00:40:46,041
(LAUGHS)

724
00:40:46,161 --> 00:40:47,921
(COMPUTER BEEPING)

725
00:40:49,961 --> 00:40:53,201
MR BROCK: We're moving into position.
It won't be long now.

726
00:40:53,281 --> 00:40:55,081
DR SIM: The Ghost is located.

727
00:40:55,561 --> 00:40:57,241
MR BROCK: Action the surgeons.

728
00:40:57,841 --> 00:40:59,841
(DOORS HISSING)

729
00:41:10,161 --> 00:41:12,201
DOCTOR: That's what Harmony Shoal
is signalling to.

730
00:41:12,521 --> 00:41:15,161
Shall we pop over and have a look?
Pretty sure no one's on board.

731
00:41:15,241 --> 00:41:17,521
How do you know?
Did you scan for lifeforms?

732
00:41:17,601 --> 00:41:19,761
No. All the lights are off.

733
00:41:20,361 --> 00:41:21,521
NARDOLE: Hmm!

734
00:41:22,521 --> 00:41:24,881
Do you have a girlfriend?

735
00:41:26,801 --> 00:41:28,001
Boyfriend?

736
00:41:29,001 --> 00:41:30,401
Well, there has been speculation.

737
00:41:31,041 --> 00:41:33,961
You do fly around New York dressed
in rubber with a big G on your chest.

738
00:41:34,121 --> 00:41:36,601
Are we very slightly stereotyping here?

739
00:41:36,761 --> 00:41:39,041
I get it. There's some stuff
you'd like to keep private.

740
00:41:39,201 --> 00:41:41,041
Was it the mask that tipped you off?

741
00:41:41,321 --> 00:41:42,641
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

742
00:41:43,081 --> 00:41:44,961
How do you cope with your double life?

743
00:41:45,161 --> 00:41:47,561
I'm nothing special.
Everyone has a day job.

744
00:41:47,641 --> 00:41:48,681
Come on.

745
00:41:48,761 --> 00:41:50,521
You spend half your time
as a regular person...

746
00:41:50,641 --> 00:41:51,961
I spend all my time that way.

747
00:41:52,081 --> 00:41:54,241
And the other half saving the world.
How do you cope?

748
00:41:54,321 --> 00:41:56,401
How do you cope with a career
and a baby?

749
00:41:59,321 --> 00:42:01,761
-How do you know I have a baby?
-I...

750
00:42:03,161 --> 00:42:04,681
Did my research.

751
00:42:07,241 --> 00:42:09,921
Uh, I have a nanny.
That's basically your answer.

752
00:42:10,041 --> 00:42:12,001
-Yes, of course.
-He's downstairs right now.

753
00:42:12,081 --> 00:42:13,641
-I see.
-And yes, I said he.

754
00:42:13,721 --> 00:42:14,921
-Yes, you did.
-Yes, I did.

755
00:42:15,001 --> 00:42:16,321
-Is that a problem?
-I'm sorry,

756
00:42:16,401 --> 00:42:20,161
it's just that guys like you sometimes
find it funny a man being a nanny.

757
00:42:20,241 --> 00:42:24,001
With respect, Miss Fletcher,
there aren't too many guys like me.

758
00:42:24,081 --> 00:42:26,321
There aren't too many guys
like Grant either.

759
00:42:33,161 --> 00:42:34,521
-You okay?
-(GASPS)

760
00:42:36,041 --> 00:42:37,481
Excuse me a minute.

761
00:42:50,961 --> 00:42:53,001
(SIRENS WAILING)

762
00:43:20,761 --> 00:43:21,881
(DOOR CLOSING)

763
00:43:22,521 --> 00:43:23,841
Bridge is this way.

764
00:43:28,041 --> 00:43:29,641
(ALARM BEEPING)

765
00:43:30,321 --> 00:43:32,601
(ALARM BLARING)

766
00:43:35,961 --> 00:43:37,201
Move.

767
00:43:40,841 --> 00:43:42,121
(KEYBOARD CLACKING)

768
00:43:45,801 --> 00:43:48,561
(BEEPING, DOORS HISSING)

769
00:43:56,241 --> 00:43:57,561
GHOST: I didn't mean to imply that

770
00:43:57,641 --> 00:43:59,321
there's something wrong
with your friend, Grant.

771
00:43:59,641 --> 00:44:01,921
You know,
not everyone can be a superhero.

772
00:44:02,001 --> 00:44:03,841
Well, not everyone can be a nanny.

773
00:44:05,561 --> 00:44:06,761
Sorry.

774
00:44:08,801 --> 00:44:10,601
He's downstairs right now.

775
00:44:10,681 --> 00:44:12,961
And he was supposed to be on a date
and he cancelled it,

776
00:44:13,041 --> 00:44:14,681
and you know
what's really bugging me about that?

777
00:44:15,201 --> 00:44:16,681
Who is he dating?

778
00:44:18,321 --> 00:44:20,561
Why is that bugging me?
Why do I care?

779
00:44:26,081 --> 00:44:27,281
What's wrong with me?

780
00:44:36,761 --> 00:44:40,481
There's probably something
I ought to tell you.

781
00:44:40,601 --> 00:44:41,801
LUCY: Grant.

782
00:44:42,201 --> 00:44:43,681
The perfect name.

783
00:44:44,361 --> 00:44:45,961
A man I take for granted.

784
00:44:46,681 --> 00:44:49,161
Erm, really if you can just look up
about now?

785
00:44:49,241 --> 00:44:52,081
Always there. Always kind. Never lies.

786
00:44:53,241 --> 00:44:54,721
I even lied to him about this dress.

787
00:44:54,801 --> 00:44:57,441
But I don't think he's ever told
a single lie to me.

788
00:44:57,521 --> 00:45:00,081
Not once. About anything.

789
00:45:01,041 --> 00:45:02,161
Not once.

790
00:45:02,361 --> 00:45:04,841
-That's very commendable.
-(DOOR OPENING)

791
00:45:05,201 --> 00:45:06,441
Good evening.

792
00:45:06,521 --> 00:45:10,281
Please take no aggressive action
or your friend's life is over.

793
00:45:10,361 --> 00:45:12,761
Mr Brock, what do you want here?

794
00:45:12,841 --> 00:45:14,281
The same thing you do, Miss Fletcher.

795
00:45:15,961 --> 00:45:17,121
His body.

796
00:45:22,281 --> 00:45:23,761
(RAPID BEEPING)

797
00:45:27,721 --> 00:45:28,801
(GRUNTS)

798
00:45:30,401 --> 00:45:31,641
Bit rubbish, isn't it?

799
00:45:32,121 --> 00:45:33,241
(WHISPERS) Don't touch anything.

800
00:45:33,321 --> 00:45:34,681
No, it's quite safe.
You're just afraid...

801
00:45:34,761 --> 00:45:36,401
- I said don't touch.
-(MUMBLES)

802
00:45:37,161 --> 00:45:38,961
See? The reactor core.

803
00:45:39,401 --> 00:45:41,121
It's cycling at critical.

804
00:45:41,201 --> 00:45:42,841
Someone's been reviving.

805
00:45:42,921 --> 00:45:44,361
This isn't a ship any more.

806
00:45:45,001 --> 00:45:47,161
-It's a giant bomb.
-Ooh...

807
00:45:48,801 --> 00:45:50,441
(GASPS) Doctor!

808
00:45:53,721 --> 00:45:55,121
(BEEPS)

809
00:45:55,921 --> 00:45:57,521
Security drones, that's all.

810
00:45:58,681 --> 00:46:00,121
So what do they want a bomb for?

811
00:46:00,201 --> 00:46:01,841
Oh, why does anybody want a bomb for?

812
00:46:01,921 --> 00:46:04,201
Surely they want to conquer the Earth,
not blow it up?

813
00:46:04,281 --> 00:46:06,281
Oh, you couldn't blow up the Earth
with this...

814
00:46:07,641 --> 00:46:09,281
But you can wipe out a city.

815
00:46:09,361 --> 00:46:11,281
-Good point, well made.
-What point?

816
00:46:11,361 --> 00:46:14,281
New York! It's not a capital city.
You're quite right.

817
00:46:14,361 --> 00:46:15,921
Oh. I don't understand.

818
00:46:16,001 --> 00:46:18,881
What if you dropped this ship
on New York? What would happen?

819
00:46:18,961 --> 00:46:22,521
The reactor core would split
and New York would vapourise.

820
00:46:22,601 --> 00:46:25,601
Not all of it.
Not all of it, Nardole.

821
00:46:26,041 --> 00:46:27,641
Remember what he said?

822
00:46:27,721 --> 00:46:29,681
The scary little German fellow.

823
00:46:29,761 --> 00:46:31,681
This building can withstand the blast

824
00:46:31,761 --> 00:46:34,281
up to four times
the strength of a nuclear explosion.

825
00:46:34,361 --> 00:46:36,481
Oh, this is very good. Very meta.

826
00:46:36,561 --> 00:46:37,641
Do you understand?

827
00:46:37,721 --> 00:46:40,241
You're stage managing an alien attack,

828
00:46:40,321 --> 00:46:42,761
when the aliens have already landed.

829
00:46:42,841 --> 00:46:44,001
But why?

830
00:46:44,081 --> 00:46:45,881
Because of what happens next
when everyone thinks that

831
00:46:45,961 --> 00:46:48,281
the Earth is being attacked
from space, what then?

832
00:46:48,361 --> 00:46:50,321
-Mass panic.
-(BANGING ON DOOR)

833
00:46:50,401 --> 00:46:52,361
(WHIMPERS) Speaking of panic.

834
00:46:52,441 --> 00:46:54,281
Don't worry,
it's triple deadlock sealed.

835
00:46:54,361 --> 00:46:55,921
It'll hold for at least ten minutes.

836
00:46:56,001 --> 00:46:58,041
The people will panic, yes.

837
00:46:58,121 --> 00:46:59,961
But what about the world leaders?

838
00:47:01,401 --> 00:47:04,601
The presidents, the kings,
the prime ministers and generals.

839
00:47:05,641 --> 00:47:07,001
What will they do?

840
00:47:07,841 --> 00:47:11,281
What do the rich old men
always do when the fighting starts?

841
00:47:11,361 --> 00:47:14,281
They'll find the safest place
to hide themselves away,

842
00:47:14,361 --> 00:47:16,441
and send all the young people to die.

843
00:47:16,521 --> 00:47:19,361
And where's the safest place
in every capital city now?

844
00:47:20,361 --> 00:47:22,601
What's the only part of
New York still standing?

845
00:47:23,081 --> 00:47:24,361
Harmony Shoal.

846
00:47:24,441 --> 00:47:27,121
New York isn't a capital city.

847
00:47:27,201 --> 00:47:28,321
(BANGING CONTINUES)

848
00:47:28,401 --> 00:47:29,841
It's a shop window.

849
00:47:30,841 --> 00:47:33,721
When the world is in danger,
come hide with us.

850
00:47:33,801 --> 00:47:38,001
Harmony Shoal will open its doors
to the terrified leaders of the world.

851
00:47:38,081 --> 00:47:39,481
And they will come running.

852
00:47:39,561 --> 00:47:40,761
DOCTOR: And a few hours later,

853
00:47:40,841 --> 00:47:45,681
every politician and commander-in-chief
will have a zip in their head.

854
00:47:47,321 --> 00:47:49,281
An alien sitting inside their skull.

855
00:47:50,561 --> 00:47:52,521
One day of terror,

856
00:47:52,601 --> 00:47:56,081
the executive authority of planet Earth
will pass to Harmony Shoal.

857
00:47:58,401 --> 00:48:00,721
It's a good plan. I like it.

858
00:48:00,801 --> 00:48:02,601
How come our side
never gets plans like that?

859
00:48:02,681 --> 00:48:04,401
The humans have no plan at all.

860
00:48:04,481 --> 00:48:06,321
(LAUGHS) That's where you're wrong.

861
00:48:07,681 --> 00:48:09,681
They have the same plan
they always have.

862
00:48:10,161 --> 00:48:11,521
-What plan?
-Me.

863
00:48:11,601 --> 00:48:13,041
(CHEERS)

864
00:48:13,961 --> 00:48:15,481
-Don't do that.
-Sorry.

865
00:48:16,641 --> 00:48:18,161
(GHOST GRUNTS)

866
00:48:19,681 --> 00:48:22,481
The operation is swift
and quite painless.

867
00:48:24,561 --> 00:48:26,881
You realise I'm talking
to my colleague in the jar?

868
00:48:27,001 --> 00:48:30,081
You'll find me a lot harder to cut open
than your previous victims.

869
00:48:30,161 --> 00:48:33,281
Harmony Shoal have been conquering
your world for five years.

870
00:48:33,361 --> 00:48:36,961
Whatever our faults,
we have the virtue of patience.

871
00:48:37,041 --> 00:48:39,841
Ghost, don't worry about me.
Do what you got to do.

872
00:48:39,921 --> 00:48:42,361
-Do anything at all and we'll kill her.
-Don't listen to him.

873
00:48:42,441 --> 00:48:43,601
MR BROCK: Remove the mask.

874
00:48:43,681 --> 00:48:45,041
I like to see their faces.

875
00:48:47,041 --> 00:48:48,401
I'm truly sorry.

876
00:48:48,521 --> 00:48:49,961
(SURGEONS GRUNTING)

877
00:48:54,601 --> 00:48:56,161
(GASPS)

878
00:48:56,241 --> 00:48:59,201
On the bright side,
at least I get to kill you.

879
00:49:01,161 --> 00:49:02,401
(GASPS)

880
00:49:04,321 --> 00:49:05,481
LUCY: No, you can't.

881
00:49:06,721 --> 00:49:09,601
That's the trouble with one hostage.
You kill me,

882
00:49:09,681 --> 00:49:11,441
and the only reason
he'll come back is for revenge.

883
00:49:11,521 --> 00:49:13,801
-You really want to deal with that?
-One hostage?

884
00:49:17,681 --> 00:49:19,321
Isn't there a child downstairs?

885
00:49:19,681 --> 00:49:20,961
(GRUNTING)

886
00:49:22,641 --> 00:49:24,481
Nobody touches that child.

887
00:49:25,561 --> 00:49:26,601
Now who are you?

888
00:49:27,761 --> 00:49:28,841
I'm the nanny.

889
00:49:31,361 --> 00:49:33,561
Stand away from the controls, Doctor.

890
00:49:33,641 --> 00:49:37,201
Any attempt to interfere with them
will precipitate the attack immediately.

891
00:49:37,281 --> 00:49:39,201
Yes, I see that. Very clever.

892
00:49:39,281 --> 00:49:42,041
One question as long as I am here.
Why haven't you done it already?

893
00:49:42,121 --> 00:49:44,601
When the time is right,
there will be no delay.

894
00:49:44,681 --> 00:49:46,161
Whoa! You told me something there.

895
00:49:46,241 --> 00:49:48,081
You told me something useful,
you shouldn't have done that.

896
00:49:48,161 --> 00:49:49,201
What did I tell you?

897
00:49:49,281 --> 00:49:51,401
You told me that
the time is currently wrong!

898
00:49:51,481 --> 00:49:54,481
Oh, it's the smile.
I don't like the smile.

899
00:49:54,561 --> 00:49:56,121
Sword of Damocles hanging over New York.

900
00:49:56,201 --> 00:49:58,321
I can't destroy it. I can't remove it.
I can't stop it falling.

901
00:49:58,401 --> 00:50:00,161
-There's only one thing I can do.
-NARDOLE: What?

902
00:50:00,241 --> 00:50:01,721
The unexpected!

903
00:50:01,801 --> 00:50:04,241
The thing about being in a room
full of buttons and switches is...

904
00:50:04,321 --> 00:50:06,081
-I love buttons and switches!
-Oh, don't! Stop!

905
00:50:06,161 --> 00:50:08,481
What are you doing?
What are you doing?

906
00:50:09,241 --> 00:50:11,161
-NARDOLE: Help!
-(MACHINE POWERING UP)

907
00:50:11,241 --> 00:50:12,921
AUTOMATED VOICE: Thrusters engaged.

908
00:50:14,041 --> 00:50:15,641
Next stop, blue rock!

909
00:50:15,721 --> 00:50:17,321
-Say whee!
-(WHIMPERS)

910
00:50:18,401 --> 00:50:20,121
-(ALARM BLARING)
-Lower shields!

911
00:50:20,201 --> 00:50:21,401
Brace for impact!

912
00:50:21,961 --> 00:50:23,401
New York is under attack.

913
00:50:25,721 --> 00:50:29,801
It occurs to me, Miss Fletcher,
I now have three hostages.

914
00:50:30,441 --> 00:50:31,881
Why don't you point the gun at me?

915
00:50:31,961 --> 00:50:33,401
What difference will it make?

916
00:50:33,961 --> 00:50:38,601
Besides, this is the one
the Ghost will come for, I think.

917
00:50:40,201 --> 00:50:41,441
Ghost!

918
00:50:42,601 --> 00:50:43,721
Can you hear me?

919
00:50:44,761 --> 00:50:46,561
Do you have super hearing?

920
00:50:47,961 --> 00:50:49,721
I'm going to kill her.

921
00:50:50,521 --> 00:50:52,481
I'm going to kill her right now!

922
00:50:53,801 --> 00:50:55,161
(ALARM BLARING)

923
00:50:55,481 --> 00:50:58,281
Stop! You're going to destroy New York!

924
00:50:58,361 --> 00:51:02,241
Of course not! Now the bomb is arming,
and the shields are down.

925
00:51:02,321 --> 00:51:04,281
-Help!
-We can use the Tardis!

926
00:51:04,361 --> 00:51:05,681
(WHIMPERING)

927
00:51:05,761 --> 00:51:09,001
Hijack the controls
and divert it into space!

928
00:51:09,081 --> 00:51:11,761
No bomb. No plan.

929
00:51:12,441 --> 00:51:16,841
-No problem.
-No! Wait, those things are out there.

930
00:51:16,921 --> 00:51:19,601
This ship is crashing, they're not
going to be worried about us.

931
00:51:20,281 --> 00:51:21,401
(WHIMPERS)

932
00:51:23,321 --> 00:51:25,801
(GRUNTS) Okay, Plan B!

933
00:51:25,881 --> 00:51:27,401
-Doctor!
-(GRUNTS)

934
00:51:27,961 --> 00:51:30,081
-Help me!
-Oh, you'll be fine.

935
00:51:30,161 --> 00:51:32,761
This ship will have blown
before you've been strangled to death.

936
00:51:32,841 --> 00:51:35,041
-Oh, what's Plan B?
-I have no idea!

937
00:51:35,121 --> 00:51:37,001
But it's going to be a very big relief
when I think of it.

938
00:51:37,081 --> 00:51:39,321
You are completely out of your mind!

939
00:51:39,401 --> 00:51:40,841
How is that news to anyone?

940
00:51:40,921 --> 00:51:44,041
Look, I know you miss her,
but couldn't you just write a poem?

941
00:51:44,121 --> 00:51:46,001
Excellent! The controls are locked.

942
00:51:46,081 --> 00:51:48,681
But they've still got a lot of
enough give, means I can take aim.

943
00:51:48,761 --> 00:51:50,481
NARDOLE: At what?
DOCTOR: New York.

944
00:51:50,561 --> 00:51:53,601
There's exactly one chance
and that is all you need.

945
00:51:53,721 --> 00:51:55,921
(CRYING) No!

946
00:51:57,241 --> 00:51:58,721
(RUMBLING)

947
00:52:03,001 --> 00:52:05,081
MR BROCK: No. No, it's too soon.

948
00:52:06,441 --> 00:52:09,361
DOCTOR:
Grant! Grant! This is the Doctor!

949
00:52:09,801 --> 00:52:13,241
You're the only living thing on Earth
that can hear this frequency.

950
00:52:13,321 --> 00:52:14,441
Look up!

951
00:52:14,681 --> 00:52:16,241
We're coming right at you.

952
00:52:16,921 --> 00:52:20,321
If that thing hits the ground,
then New York is finished.

953
00:52:20,401 --> 00:52:21,761
Over to you.

954
00:52:25,401 --> 00:52:28,841
(IN A GRUFF VOICE)
Mrs Lombard, please get down.

955
00:52:28,921 --> 00:52:29,961
What? (GASPS)

956
00:52:33,561 --> 00:52:35,121
-Nardole!
-(WHIMPERS) Yeah!

957
00:52:35,201 --> 00:52:36,601
Brace for impact!

958
00:52:36,681 --> 00:52:39,321
(NARDOLE WHIMPERS, SCREAMS)

959
00:52:53,641 --> 00:52:55,121
(TYRES SCREECHING)

960
00:52:55,721 --> 00:52:57,441
(PEOPLE SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

961
00:53:02,601 --> 00:53:03,961
(GRUNTS)

962
00:53:22,561 --> 00:53:24,401
(ELECTRICITY CRACKLING)

963
00:53:39,401 --> 00:53:40,841
(GRUNTS)

964
00:53:42,521 --> 00:53:44,361
Nardole. Nardole!

965
00:53:44,441 --> 00:53:46,681
NARDOLE: (IN ROBOTIC VOICE)
Okay, one more...

966
00:53:46,761 --> 00:53:48,961
Nardole, it worked!

967
00:53:49,961 --> 00:53:52,001
The reactor core didn't split.

968
00:53:52,601 --> 00:53:53,761
Why not?

969
00:53:54,001 --> 00:53:55,401
Shock absorber.

970
00:53:58,281 --> 00:54:01,001
Mrs Lombard, I realise in many ways
it would've been better

971
00:54:01,081 --> 00:54:03,921
to have mentioned something
about this earlier in the evening,

972
00:54:04,001 --> 00:54:06,481
but please don't slap me.

973
00:54:06,561 --> 00:54:09,201
I think I'm holding a giant bomb.

974
00:54:09,761 --> 00:54:11,401
(WHOOSHING)

975
00:54:21,801 --> 00:54:24,281
There. On you go. Take a look at him.

976
00:54:24,361 --> 00:54:27,441
That's why you don't stand a chance.
You want to know why?

977
00:54:27,521 --> 00:54:29,121
He's actually left-handed.

978
00:54:29,201 --> 00:54:31,561
Sorry, instinct.
I couldn't let go of this.

979
00:54:37,561 --> 00:54:39,161
(DOCTOR EXCLAIMING)

980
00:54:39,481 --> 00:54:41,801
If you two are about to get excited,

981
00:54:41,881 --> 00:54:44,041
maybe you could get rid
of that spaceship first?

982
00:54:45,401 --> 00:54:46,601
You know what?

983
00:54:47,601 --> 00:54:49,881
I think I prefer you
in your superhero costume.

984
00:54:50,041 --> 00:54:52,761
It's a bit difficult for me
to change right now.

985
00:54:53,641 --> 00:54:55,001
I'll do it for you.

986
00:54:55,241 --> 00:54:56,441
(BREATH TREMBLING)

987
00:55:09,561 --> 00:55:10,801
DOCTOR: Grant...

988
00:55:11,681 --> 00:55:14,761
Grant, uh, remember
when you're finished,

989
00:55:15,321 --> 00:55:17,361
to throw that thing into the sun.

990
00:55:19,041 --> 00:55:21,041
Jennifer's still downstairs!

991
00:55:22,161 --> 00:55:23,881
(COOING ON MONITOR)

992
00:55:24,161 --> 00:55:25,561
So, Doctor?

993
00:55:26,521 --> 00:55:28,041
-You think this is over?
-Yeah.

994
00:55:28,681 --> 00:55:31,561
-(GRUNTS)
-Your bomb's gone, your plan's finished.

995
00:55:32,241 --> 00:55:36,481
And look, there's UNIT on the way
to close your head office.

996
00:55:36,961 --> 00:55:38,801
It's almost like
they've been tipped off.

997
00:55:39,081 --> 00:55:41,001
The vengeance of Harmony Shoal is known

998
00:55:41,081 --> 00:55:43,041
and feared throughout
the Five-star System.

999
00:55:43,121 --> 00:55:45,241
Ooh! Is it? Is it really?

1000
00:55:45,321 --> 00:55:47,041
Well, I'd like to
stick around and listen,

1001
00:55:47,121 --> 00:55:48,521
but it's been a very long night.

1002
00:55:48,601 --> 00:55:51,361
-(BABY CRYING ON THE MONITOR)
-Also, someone needs changing.

1003
00:55:52,041 --> 00:55:53,961
You're not the only one
that's full of it.

1004
00:55:55,281 --> 00:55:56,441
(DOOR OPENING)

1005
00:55:57,281 --> 00:55:59,001
SOLDIER: Let's go! Let's go!
Let's go! Let's go!

1006
00:55:59,081 --> 00:56:00,761
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

1007
00:56:01,441 --> 00:56:02,881
Get down, down here!

1008
00:56:02,961 --> 00:56:04,641
WOMAN: Hey, get off me!

1009
00:56:04,721 --> 00:56:06,121
SOLDIER: And he was like this
when you found him?

1010
00:56:06,201 --> 00:56:07,481
MAN: Yes, sir!

1011
00:56:07,561 --> 00:56:09,241
(INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER)

1012
00:56:12,641 --> 00:56:13,841
SOLDIER: Wait here.

1013
00:56:14,321 --> 00:56:16,161
I'm putting a call into Osgood.

1014
00:56:23,681 --> 00:56:25,361
So no more Ghost then?

1015
00:56:25,441 --> 00:56:26,761
Ah, laid to rest.

1016
00:56:27,481 --> 00:56:29,241
-LUCY: Sure?
-Yeah, of course I'm sure.

1017
00:56:29,321 --> 00:56:31,841
I mean, life's not a comic book.
Right, Doctor?

1018
00:56:31,921 --> 00:56:33,641
Possibly I'm not
the right person to ask.

1019
00:56:33,841 --> 00:56:37,041
What if something happens?
What if the whole world is in danger?

1020
00:56:37,721 --> 00:56:41,081
Well, you know,
maybe I'll keep the outfit then?

1021
00:56:41,361 --> 00:56:42,801
-You know, just in case?
-Mmm.

1022
00:56:42,881 --> 00:56:46,041
The world will be fine.
I'd been away for a while, but I'm back.

1023
00:56:47,281 --> 00:56:48,761
I'll take care of anything
that comes up.

1024
00:56:48,881 --> 00:56:50,201
-You were away?
-Yeah.

1025
00:56:50,281 --> 00:56:52,961
Twenty-four years. What a night.

1026
00:56:54,481 --> 00:56:55,721
Where did you go?

1027
00:56:56,361 --> 00:56:57,641
Wrong question.

1028
00:57:01,441 --> 00:57:02,561
What was her name?

1029
00:57:08,401 --> 00:57:10,641
I'm sure that I must be busy now,
I better go.

1030
00:57:11,721 --> 00:57:14,121
-You okay?
-Yes! Yes, yes! I'm okay.

1031
00:57:14,201 --> 00:57:15,801
(TOY SQUEAKING)

1032
00:57:20,241 --> 00:57:21,401
Things end.

1033
00:57:23,161 --> 00:57:24,361
That's all.

1034
00:57:27,281 --> 00:57:28,681
Everything ends...

1035
00:57:30,481 --> 00:57:32,161
And it's always sad.

1036
00:57:34,161 --> 00:57:38,881
But everything begins again too,
and that's always happy.

1037
00:57:41,761 --> 00:57:42,761
Be happy.

1038
00:57:44,801 --> 00:57:46,481
I'll look after everything else.

1039
00:57:49,361 --> 00:57:50,441
Nardole.

1040
00:57:50,521 --> 00:57:51,601
Hey, Doctor?

1041
00:57:52,361 --> 00:57:54,161
-(SQUEAKS)
-Keep it real.

1042
00:58:04,961 --> 00:58:07,321
Her name was River Song.

1043
00:58:08,521 --> 00:58:11,201
They were together for a while
and they were very happy.

1044
00:58:11,881 --> 00:58:13,081
And then she died,

1045
00:58:13,641 --> 00:58:16,281
a long time ago in a library.

1046
00:58:16,681 --> 00:58:18,041
You sure he's gonna be all right?

1047
00:58:18,161 --> 00:58:19,961
(CHUCKLES) He's the Doctor.

1048
00:58:20,921 --> 00:58:23,961
He's very brave and he's very silly.

1049
00:58:24,041 --> 00:58:27,441
And I think for a time
he's going to be very sad.

1050
00:58:28,401 --> 00:58:32,281
But I promise,
in the end he'll be all right.

1051
00:58:33,481 --> 00:58:34,761
I'll make sure of it.

1052
00:58:35,441 --> 00:58:36,561
Bye.

1053
00:58:39,601 --> 00:58:41,841
-(SIGHS)
-You never explained.

1054
00:58:42,601 --> 00:58:45,281
Who exactly is he? Doctor who?

1055
00:58:46,961 --> 00:58:47,961
(TARDIS POWERING UP)

1056
00:58:48,041 --> 00:58:49,481
GRANT: Doctor...

1057
00:58:50,881 --> 00:58:52,321
Mysterio.

1058
00:58:58,401 --> 00:59:00,041
(WHOOSHING)

1059
00:59:09,601 --> 00:59:11,281
I'm Bill. I serve chips.

1060
00:59:11,361 --> 00:59:14,201
He's a professor or a lecturer.
Or as I call him...

1061
00:59:14,281 --> 00:59:15,361
Doctor what?

1062
00:59:15,441 --> 00:59:17,441
And now we go everywhere...

1063
00:59:18,641 --> 00:59:20,641
-It's like a... Kitchen!
-Spaceship.

1064
00:59:20,921 --> 00:59:22,001
Any space.

1065
00:59:22,081 --> 00:59:24,281
Where are we?
Which way is Earth? What's a Dalek?

1066
00:59:24,401 --> 00:59:25,521
Can I use the toilet?

1067
00:59:25,601 --> 00:59:26,961
Any time.

1068
00:59:27,041 --> 00:59:28,041
Get in!

1069
00:59:28,121 --> 00:59:29,481
Whoa!

1070
00:59:29,561 --> 00:59:31,601
And now I see everything differently.

1071
00:59:31,681 --> 00:59:32,881
(SCREAMING)

1072
00:59:33,801 --> 00:59:35,921
(DALEKS SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

1073
00:59:36,041 --> 00:59:37,641
-Where are we?
-Basically in the middle of a war.

1074
00:59:37,801 --> 00:59:40,521
-(SCREAMS)
-And it's not as bad as it sounds.

1075
00:59:41,441 --> 00:59:42,441
I'm the Doctor.

1076
00:59:42,521 --> 00:59:44,361
I will save all your lives
and when I do,

1077
00:59:44,441 --> 00:59:46,481
you will spend the rest of them
wondering who I was.

1078
00:59:49,761 --> 00:59:50,801
Are you out of your mind?

1079
00:59:50,881 --> 00:59:52,921
Yes. Completely.
But that's not a recent thing.

